d asking for our beverage order.  It took another 10mins. for the waiter to notice that we ready to order.  We were actually ready when the busboy came, but the waiters just kept on passing by looking like they were on a mission for something else.  Then, after 25-30mins. our food FINALLY arrived.  They didn't seem short staffed; there were plenty of them walking around.  I just don't think that it was as streamlined as it could have been.  Each person had a job and could only do that job.  Good thing I don't rate on that.\n\nthe food:\nSo, with all the negative things I've said of this place, I can't knock on the food.  Wow!  wow!  Truly amazing, succulent, flavorful entrees.  Wow!  For two people, we ordered way too much.  But, I couldn't have been more happy with our choices.  Three of the four, we picked off the Chef's Specials.  On this page, dishes run at around $20 per, with the snapper at $40.  Most other dishes in the menu run at $10 or less.  The one that we ordered in the $10 range was ok, but not divine.  Again, everything we ordered on that page was perfect!  \n\n - drunken noodle seabass\ngood flavor (slightly oily) on the noodles, bass cooked/crisp to perfection\n - curry short rib\ntender, curry had good spices (warning: heavy coconut milk)\n - the garlic prawns\nso good you could even eat the shell... and big too!\n\nLast Words: Perhaps, THEE BEST THAI FOOD I'VE EVER HAD!\nI highly recommend options off the Chef's Special.  They're twice as much, but worth every penny.  ...Just leave the calorie counter at home.  Haha.", "There are plenty of reviews of Lotus of Siam, thanks to consistent buzz amongst locals, tourists, and food magazines. Know going in that you can't just waltz in, pick something off the menu and expect to be stunned. Their menu is extensive and contains most of the standard Thai dishes, most of which are pretty average. But if you know what to order you can have an amazing experience. They feature a lot of Northern Thai dishes which are unique to most Westerners, many of which are pretty mind-blowing. When in doubt, ask your waiter -- the staff knows what's popular. I've been here around 20 times in the past year, and here are my favorites, more or less in order of awesomeness:\n\n1) Spicy chicken wings (appetizer)\n2) Special crispy duck curry with Panang sauce\n3) Drunken noodles with Sea Bass\n4) Fish cakes (appetizer)\n5) Crying Tiger Beef (basically just tender grilled beef steak with a good sauce)\n6) Thai beef jerky (appetizer)\n\nStick with those, especially the first 4, and you'll be happy.", "We went for the first time to try the infamous lunch buffet. The buffet was small, but everything on it tasted homemade and delicious. We eat at a lot of buffets, and normally the small ones end up being a waste. This was not! The service was a little slow, and it wasn't very crowded, so both of those things surprised us. The curry chicken they had on the buffet made up for most of it, and the most interesting and unique tasting hot and sour soup we have ever had. Each spoonful had a different and complex flavor. We tried to figure out what all was in it that wasn't obvious, but couldn't. We would like to come back and try ordering off the menu for dinner.", "We've been here twice.  The food is always good & the service slow.\nI just don't know if it' s the best in the country, but I don't have many other comps...\n\nI do love the shopping center that it is in.   So many random spots to explore.\n\nOh & fantastic Rieslings!", "Well it's not the fanciest spot in Vegas. It's off the strip in a strip mall. The strip mall looked pretty interesting. Lots of Korean restaurants, a saloon, travel agency, billiards and karaoke. \n\nAnyway, this place is supposed to be pretty famous I guess...saw lots of celeb pics on wall and voted best Thai food in America or something. I had the lunch buffet which was only $8.99. Not a bad deal for unlimited pad thai, chicken curry, eggrolls, sauteed veggies, couple di