ow up after they presented us with the menu.  We lingered for about 10 minutes chatting after dessert, which prompted a woman to come out twice to clear our table. She was all smiles, though, and we left because the place is pretty tiny and we didn't want to cause people to wait. There were perhaps two parties in the waiting room when we left, but there were at least two free tables (besides ours).\n\nI'd come back again, but I'm not sure it's the \"best Thai restaurant in the country.\"  I took photos of our meals, which I added to the others for this restaurant. They are cell-phone quality but I tried to make them look decent.  Our plates really did look lovely when served.", "My 2nd favorite restaurant in Las Vegas after \"Himalayan Cuisine\". The lunch buffet is ok but dinner here is superb. I like smaller friendlier atmospheres and a relaxed ambiance with fantastic food at reasonable prices without the pretense thats usually displayed at a lot of sub par casino restaurants. I really like the house special flat noodles with crawfish. Their wine list is fantastic and much more reasonably priced than other places that boast great wine lists. Alas, the beer is limited to the standard weak Asian lagers and domestics, but if its fantastic beers I want I just go to the Himalayan Cuisine instead. The sommelier here is a very affable man and after chatting him up I was able to twist his arm and offer him a little taster of the Bergstrom Pinot Noir I had one night. All in all, fantastic Thai food that deserves its well-reviewed reputation, great wine list, friendly wait-staff that doesn't stand on ceremony, bland beer selection and decent but not necessarily fantastic lunch buffet.", "Put the buffet plate down... step away from the counter and move off the strip for a bit.  OK so it's not that far off the strip and yes if you drive down Sahara you'll see the restaurant front and you may just pass by and say forget it.  That was my SO's reaction as we drove by, but trust 