[2009, "season1"]	["3.5 stars\n\nI've now come to this restaurant three times and its been hit or miss.  Sometimes I have a great meal and sometimes it's a mediocre meal at best.  \n\nSome dishes that stick out in my mind:\n\nSoups: I've had a few different soups, but they've all been really good.  When they ask you how hot you'd like it, from a scale of 1-10, they aren't messing around.  I had the 3 and was really feeeling the heat.  Don't take the heat for granted.\n\nCrispy Sea Bass and Drunken Noodles: Waaaaay overpriced.  For $23, you'd expect a lot more.  What you get are a few small crispy fillets on top of a square chunk of chow fun noodles.  Nothing special for $23.\n\nGarlic Prawns: I think these were around $20.  What I really like about these is that the skin is mostly peeled off and attached just at the base and they deep fry the whole thing.  The flavors are great and I highly recommend the dish...albeit a bit overpriced.  \n\nThey also have an extremely impressive wine list with like 7 pages of rieslings.\n\nI feel like the food here is good, but I'm not sure if it's anything truly spectacular that everyone has made it out to be.", "4.5 stars\n\nThis is the best Thai food I've had in Las Vegas and some of the best I've had anywhere.  I've been here many times for lunch, and I try to get there before 11:45am because often a line starts forming at noon.\n\nI had the buffet once, and it was so-so  All the other times were ordered from the menu.  My fav is the panang curry - they do a great job with it.  Sweet, spicy, a lot of depth and subtle flavors.  \n\nThe one thing that's inconsistent there is the spice level.  I've ordered a 9 and it wasn't so spicy while other times Ive ordered a 7 and it was spicy as a regular 9.", "Ate at Lotus of Siam again last weekend. Yum! Mr. Tracy A. tried one of the northern Thai dishes with jack fruit -- a departure from what you usually see on a Thai menu. It was delicious, with a spicy tomato-y broth. I'm even willing 