ul blend of noodles, seafood, greens and garlic. But the noodles were clumped together in a big wad with the greens and seafood around. The shrimp, scallops, and surimi were just right and full of flavor. On the other hand the squid and the mussels were flavorless and a bit too chewy. On the plus side, I thought they got the heat just right. We ordered both dishes medium hot (5 out of 10) and thought they were perfect; no sweat on the brow but nicely intense. If I lived in Vegas, I would return because they had one of the most extensive and interesting menus I have ever seen.", "We've been here twice now.  Food is excellent.  Service is always great.  Very cheerful. Some of the best Thai food that we've been able to find in Vegas! Will definitely be going back for more.", "We've come here for dinner (very good), but the crowning jewel is the lunch buffet for $8.99, only offered on the weekdays. This is a small restaurant located in the Commercial Center (doesn't look like much outside, I know), but so many regulars come here, so this is a busy lunch buffet. On the walls are framed pictures of the owner/cook with various people (Mayor Oscar Goodman is one of them), as well as notable articles of recognition- numerous \"best of\" and such. \n\nYou pay at the door, before getting seated. If there are already a number of diners in the restaurant, it could be a few minutes- but not more than 15 minutes. Service is pretty good. Drink orders are filled right away. The dirty plates are taken off your table pretty quickly. \n\nThe buffet is not large, but it is high-quality. The yellow curry with tender chunks of potato and chicken is my husband's favorite- he said that he could drink the sauce with a straw. There are two or three stir fried dishes with a good mix of noodles, vegetables and chicken. Also on the menu: soup, salad, fruit, chicken wings, french fries, rangoons, dessert spring rolls (banana & coconut), jello squares, shrimp chips, and rice. I might be missing a 