 Thai Spice (where I always get the orange chicken...).\n\nAs you can probably tell by most of the reviews, the food ranges from good to outstanding.  I'll let you read everyone elses reviews since, like I said, I'm not well versed when it comes to thai.  However, the one thing I do feel I need to talk about is the service.  It is absolutely great that the dining space has been expanded, allowing more tables for guests to be seated at.  What I don't like is that the waiters/waitresses did not appear to be assigned to a specific area or set of tables.  There were a lot of employees working during the Friday night I went there, many of whom served my table at one point or another.  I don't think we had the same server visit our table twice that night, which made it annoying when trying to flag someone down.  I can't count the number of times I saw a server with a tray of food standing around looking lost and confused, wondering which table the order belonged to.  Trying to get more water, order more dishes, order dessert, or get the check was a trial in patience.\n\nDoes the quality of the food outweigh my bad experience with the service?  Yes, it does.  But when i recommend this place to friends, the recommendation will always be accompanied by a footnote to be prepared to do a lot of sitting and waiting.", "I haven't been here in a LONG while (since I left Las Vegas back in early 2009), but I have to say that this restaurant is definitely one of my favorite Las Vegas haunts. For the longest time, I had always gone to Komol next door (across the parking lot) and was always reticent to try LoS. Needless to say, I only wish I had gone more often. LoS has become my gold standard for all Thai restaurants to be compared to. Every dish I've had here has met or exceeded expectations - the balance of flavour (sweet vs. sour vs. heat, etc),  the quality of ingredients,  and the preparation. From the Drunken Noodles to the curries to the more exotic dishes like whole catfish (